NATION BRIEFS																																												London, Nov. 7 (PTI): A Sikh student of Indian origin has been barred from her school in Britain for refusing to take off her iron bangle. 																																												Aberdare Girls School in south Wales has temporarily suspended Sarika Singh, 14, after she declined to remove the kara, a symbol of her faith, The Guardian reported today. The school cited violation of uniform guidelines as reason for her temporary exclusion. Singhs family is planning to seek legal recourse soon. 																																												New Delhi (PTI): School students will be issued smart cards containing information about their annual health report as part of the national school health programme to be launched soon, Union health minister Anbumani Ramadoss said.																																												New Delhi (PTI): Businessmen can lend money to their suppliers to ensure regular supply of goods, and such an act cannot be termed illegal or classified as money lending, the Supreme Court has said.																																												Durban (PTI): Adam Habib, an Indian-origin political scientist from South Africa, has been permanently denied entry to the US. Habib, the deputy vice-chancellor of the University of Johannesburg, said the ban was because of his anti-America ideology. 																																												Mumbai (PTI): Amitabh Bachchans mother Teji Bachchan, 93, who has been in Lilavati hospital for almost a year now, was shifted to its intensive care unit after she fell seriously ill on Wednesday, sources said. 																																												 New Delhi (PTI): Delhi High Court has directed Tihar Jail officials to put petition boxes in which inmates can drop their complaints, which would be considered by the National Human Rights Commission. The court has been looking into the living conditions of the prisoners after deaths of inmates because of overcrowding and poor sanitation were reported.
